<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="356" pageId="8" pageNumber="355" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1127,1216,1592]" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,265,1216,1240]" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hartig" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[270,488,1217,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscicornis">
<emphasis box="[270,488,1217,1240]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">Alloxysta fuscicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is mainly characterized by closed radial cell, pronotal carinae, and smooth propodeum. It is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[571,668,1249,1272]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="victrix">
<emphasis box="[571,668,1249,1272]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">A. victrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they can be easily differentiated by (i) the size of radial cell: the radial cell of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hartig" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[574,721,1281,1304]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscicornis">
<emphasis box="[574,721,1281,1304]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">A. fuscicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 2.7 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[1040,1118,1280,1304]" captionStart="Figs 5–14" captionStartId="5.[113,150,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[143,1063,220,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-15@5.[137,1066,217,1473]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 5–14. Types of radial cell in forewing of Alloxysta species. 5 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 6 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 7 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 8 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 9 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 10 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 11 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 12 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 13 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 14 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740344/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) while the radial cell is 3.0 times as long as wide in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[711,810,1313,1336]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="victrix">
<emphasis box="[711,810,1313,1336]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">A. victrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[826,892,1312,1336]" captionStart="Figs 5–14" captionStartId="5.[113,150,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[143,1063,220,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-15@5.[137,1066,217,1473]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 5–14. Types of radial cell in forewing of Alloxysta species. 5 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 6 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 7 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 8 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 9 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 10 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 11 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 12 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 13 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 14 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740344/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), and by (ii) the setation on propodeum: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hartig" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[369,516,1345,1368]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscicornis">
<emphasis box="[369,516,1345,1368]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">A. fuscicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the propodeum completely covered with dense setae while in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[243,340,1377,1400]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="victrix">
<emphasis box="[243,340,1377,1400]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">A. victrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the propodeum lacks setae at the longitudinal area whereas the carinae are present in other 
<taxonomicName box="[324,445,1408,1432]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Charipinae">Charipinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1127,1216,1592]" lastBlockId="9.[113,1089,219,339]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="356" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,372,1440,1464]" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">Short redescription.</emphasis>
Head, mesosoma and metasoma brown; scape, pedicel, F1 and F2 yellow and F3–F12 yellowish brown; legs yellow; veins brown. Female antennae 13-segmented; F1–F3 smooth and thinner than remaining ones, F4–F12 club-shaped, with rhinaria; F1 longer than pedicel and F2, F2 longer than F3, F3 shorter than F4 (
<figureCitation box="[870,950,1536,1560]" captionStart="Figs 15–24" captionStartId="6.[151,188,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[191,1087,219,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[191,1087,219,1470]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 15–24. Antenna of Alloxysta species. 15 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 16 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 17 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 18 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 19 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 20 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 21 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 22 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 23 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 24 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740346" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740346/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="355">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Male antennae 14-segmented; with the same proportions as in female but F1–F3 bowed (F1 slightly bowed while F2 and F3 clearly bowed). Pronotum covered with setae with two carinae present and clearly visible. Propodeum with abundant setae and without carinae. Forewing longer than body; radial cell closed, 2.7 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[658,736,283,308]" captionStart="Figs 5–14" captionStartId="5.[113,150,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[143,1063,220,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-15@5.[137,1066,217,1473]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 5–14. Types of radial cell in forewing of Alloxysta species. 5 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 6 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 7 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 8 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 9 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 10 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 11 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 12 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 13 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 14 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740344/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="356">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
